05082nam a22007935i 9780226695006DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202020ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2019049797  a97802266950067 a10.7208/97802266950062doi  a(DE-B1597)549367  a(OCoLC)1155636467  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aHM636b.G47 2020 4aHM636b.G47 2021 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a306.42231 aGeorge, Alys X., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Naked Truth :bViennese Modernism and the Body /cAlys X. George. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (328 p.) :b43 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tNote on Translations -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Body on Display: Staging the Other, Shaping the Self -- t2. The Body in Pieces: Viennese Literature’s Anatomies -- t3. The Patient’s Body: Working- Class Women in the Clinic -- t4. The Body in Motion: Staging Silent Expression -- tEpilogue -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aViennese modernism is often described in terms of a fin-de-siècle fascination with the psyche. But this stereotype of the movement as essentially cerebral overlooks a rich cultural history of the body. The Naked Truth, an interdisciplinary tour de force, addresses this lacuna, fundamentally recasting the visual, literary, and performative cultures of Viennese modernism through an innovative focus on the corporeal. Alys X. George explores the modernist focus on the flesh by turning our attention to the second Vienna medical school, which revolutionized the field of anatomy in the 1800s. As she traces the results of this materialist influence across a broad range of cultural forms—exhibitions, literature, portraiture, dance, film, and more—George brings into dialogue a diverse group of historical protagonists, from canonical figures such as Egon Schiele, Arthur Schnitzler, Joseph Roth, and Hugo von Hofmannsthal to long-overlooked ones, including author and doctor Marie Pappenheim, journalist Else Feldmann, and dancers Grete Wiesenthal, Gertrud Bodenwieser, and Hilde Holger. She deftly blends analyses of popular and “high” culture, laying to rest the notion that Viennese modernism was an exclusively male movement. The Naked Truth uncovers the complex interplay of the physical and the aesthetic that shaped modernism and offers a striking new interpretation of this fascinating moment in the history of the West.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aHuman body in literature. 0aHuman body in popular culture. 0aHuman bodyzAustriazViennaxHistoryy19th century. 0aHuman bodyzAustriazViennaxHistoryy20th century. 0aHuman figure in art. 0aModernism (Art)zAustriazViennaxHistoryy19th century. 0aModernism (Art)zAustriazViennaxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aFirst Austrian Republic.  aRed Vienna.  aVienna.  aViennese modernism.  abody culture.  acultural history.  acultural studies.  afin de siècle.  ahistory of body.  amodernism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020 Englishz978311070473008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020z9783110704525oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP Frontlist eBook-Package 2020z978311069309640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226695006423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter